# **PART I — THE MINIATURISED ARCHIMEDEAN RAY**

Leonardo's burning mirror programme was not merely an industrial heating project. It was the world's first controlled, scaled-down implementation of the Archimedean burning ray — the legendary concave mirror weapon attributed to Archimedes at the Siege of Syracuse in 212 BC, which Leonardo had studied directly. In his memoranda, "Archimedes" appears as a specific book entry. He was not simply referencing a myth; he was reading the primary engineering claim and engineering it downward to controllable human scale.

*"**With this any dyer**'**s cauldron can be made to boil; and by it a pool will be heated, because there will always be boiling water.**"** — Leonardo, Codex Arundel f.87v–88r*

This is not the language of weapon design. It is the language of controlled thermal application — sustained, regulated, repeatable. The dyer's cauldron is the tell: a dyer needs a CONTROLLED and SUSTAINED heat source for cloth processing. Leonardo, who documented cloth preparation chemistry in the Madrid I back matter, was thinking about applying focused solar energy to textile surfaces in a controlled way.

**CORE HYPOTHESIS: Leonardo used a precision concave mirror in focused Mediterranean sunlight to produce controlled cellulose oxidation-dehydration on paper and linen surfaces. The paper tests survive in the Codex Arundel and Codex Atlanticus as areas of suppressed UV fluorescence that have been attributed to age, foxing, or handling damage.**

# **PART II — STURP FIBRIL DATA: THE TARGET SIGNATURE**

Any test mark on Leonardo's paper must match this signature to be a valid candidate. The STURP analysis of the Turin Shroud body image establishes the following confirmed physical properties:

| **Property** | **Shroud Measurement** | **What to look for on paper** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Depth of coloration | 0.2 micrometres — outermost fibrils only | Surface yellowing only; no penetration through paper cross-section |
| Chemical mechanism | Cellulose oxidation-dehydration: C-C bonds → C=C conjugation (no added substance) | Same chemical signature: FTIR shows C=C stretch at 1620-1640 cm⁻¹ |
| UV fluorescence | IMAGE ZONES ARE DARK (suppressed fluorescence) vs bright surrounding cloth | Test marks appear DARK under 365nm UV-A; surrounding paper fluoresces normally |
| Visual appearance | Sepia/yellowish-brown, low contrast in normal light | Appears as slight yellowing; easily misattributed to foxing or age |
| Directionality | None — no stroke direction, no brush marks | No stroke pattern; edges defined by focal geometry (circular/elliptical) |
| 3D information | Tonal gradient encodes distance from cloth surface | Gradient encodes distance from focal plane; darkest = closest to focus |

KEY DISCRIMINATOR: Under 365nm UV-A illumination, natural foxing (organic: fungal, acid) fluoresces BRIGHTLY (yellow-green/white). Solar-scorched cellulose fluoresces DARK because the C=C conjugation quenches the fluorescence signal. This is the diagnostic tool. Look for dark spots under UV where surrounding paper is bright.

