## **CANDIDATE 4 — THE ENCRYPTED CLUSTER**

### **Codex Atlanticus, 1513–15 Cipher Group | Biblioteca Ambrosiana, Milan**

During 1513–15, while in the service of Giuliano de' Medici at the Vatican in Rome, Leonardo was planning large-scale concave mirror production and encrypted his notes on this programme in cipher — uniquely in the entire codex. The specific folios within this cluster are not all catalogued to individual CA folio numbers in publicly available sources, but the cluster corresponds to the Vatican period notes in the CA.

| **Item** | **Detail** |
| --- | --- |
| Date | 1513–15 — Vatican period. Giuliano de' Medici patron. |
| Confirmed content | Over 200 mirror designs across CA and Codex Arundel. Notes encrypted in cipher. Planning for industrial-scale large concave mirror production. |
| Why encrypted | Leonardo did NOT encrypt his clock escapement. He did not encrypt his gear theory. He encrypted the mirror programme. If the mirrors were only for heating dyers' vats, encryption would be unnecessary. The encryption signals a more sensitive application. |
| Timeline relevance | 1513–15 is also when the Shroud was at Chambéry, in Savoy under the House of Savoy. Leonardo was at the Vatican with access to the highest levels of ecclesiastical patronage, under Leo X (Giovanni de' Medici) and his brother Giuliano. |
| Search target | Identify the specific cipher-script folios in the CA Vatican cluster. Examine under 365nm UV-A for suppressed-fluorescence spots. These are the highest-sensitivity pages in the entire corpus for this investigation. |

**CRITICAL: If test marks are found on the encrypted mirror cluster pages, they establish not only that Leonardo tested solar scorching on paper but that he considered the process sensitive enough to protect. This is the strongest possible documentary anchor for the Shroud hypothesis.**

## **CANDIDATE 5 — THE CAUSTIC REFLECTION LATHE PAGE**

### **Codex Arundel 263, optics/caustics/lathe folios c.1503–5 | British Library, London**

The British Library catalogue specifically identifies a page or pages in the Codex Arundel with: "Notes and diagram on optics, concerning the caustics of reflection; drawing of a lathe designed to manufacture concave mirrors; mathematical calculations, c.1503–5."

- A lathe designed to manufacture concave mirrors is not just a diagram. It is an engineering specification for a precision instrument-making process. Leonardo was designing the production machinery, not just the mirror geometry.

- The "caustics of reflection" are the focal zones — the exact geometry of where the solar energy concentrates. This is the theoretical underpinning for knowing where to place the test surface.

- A page that contains both the lathe design AND the caustic calculations is the page where Leonardo had the most complete understanding of where his mirror would focus. It is the ideal page on which to make a test mark.

- This page appears to be separate from ff.87v–88r in the current binding. Exact folio number to be confirmed from the BL digital viewer. Search for the lathe image in the digitised Arundel to identify the precise folio.

Location: The BL digitised Arundel is fully available at bl.uk/manuscripts. Search for the lathe/concave mirror manufacturing page to confirm the exact folio number, then flag it for UV examination.

# **PART IV — FULL SPECTRAL ANALYSIS PROTOCOL**

## **Stage A — Blue Filter Visual Pre-Screening (Can Be Done Now Online)**

The digitised Codex Arundel is freely available at the British Library website. The Codex Atlanticus is available via the Visual Agency (codex-atlanticus.it). The following visual pre-screening can be done on a standard monitor using any image editing software (GIMP, Photoshop, or even browser zoom).

- Go to the confirmed burning mirror folios (ff.87v–88r in Arundel; CA f.801r in Atlanticus).

- In image editing software, open the high-resolution digitised scan.

- Apply a blue channel emphasis filter (increase blue channel, reduce red and green) — this simulates the effect of a UV-A blue filter and will suppress the appearance of yellow-brown organic aging while making suppressed-fluorescence zones relatively more visible.

- Look for any area of the central page field that remains uniformly dark/muted when surrounding foxing and aging marks become more visible under the blue-enhanced view.

- Mark candidates with their approximate dimensions and position on the folio.

This visual pre-screening is only an approximation. It will not definitively confirm the solar scorch signature. It will generate a shortlist of candidate areas for the physical examination in Stage B.

## **Stage B — Physical UV-A Photoluminescence Imaging**

This requires access to the physical manuscripts. The protocol is established and has been used on both target collections.

**Equipment (as used in 2023 Politecnico di Milano / CA f.843 study):**

- UV-A source: mercury vapor lamps with DUG11 filter, excitation centred at 365nm, FWHM < 10nm.

- Detector: hyperspectral camera, sensitivity 400–900nm, spectral resolution ~4nm at 600nm. Fourier Transform-based.

- Alternatively: standard UV-A hand lamp (365nm) with digital camera and yellow-barrier filter for simple visual UV fluorescence imaging as a first pass.

**Examination procedure:**

- Illuminate the target folio with 365nm UV-A radiation in a darkened examination room.

- Photograph under UV illumination using a camera with yellow/orange barrier filter to exclude the reflected UV and capture only the fluorescence emission.

- In the UV fluorescence image: normal aged paper appears BRIGHT (cream/yellow-green fluorescence). Organic foxing appears BRIGHT (often brighter than paper). Solar scorch zones appear DARK (suppressed fluorescence).

- Identify any circular, elliptical, or gradient dark spots in the central field of the burning mirror pages.

- Record dimensions, position on folio, and relationship to the surrounding ink/drawing content.

## **Stage C — Chemical Confirmation (Micro-ATR-FTIR)**

If Stage B identifies a candidate dark spot, chemical confirmation is by micro-ATR-FTIR spectroscopy at the boundary of the spot. This is minimally invasive (can be done without sampling if contact ATR head used on the paper surface).

**Target spectral signature:**

- C=C conjugation: absorption at 1620–1640 cm⁻¹ (alkene C=C stretch) — this is the bond created by cellulose oxidation-dehydration, identical to the Shroud image chemistry.

- Reduced OH: decrease in broad OH stretch at 3200–3600 cm⁻¹ — dehydration signature.

- Carbonyl increase: C=O absorption at 1730–1750 cm⁻¹ — oxidation product.

- If the candidate spot shows the same IR signature as confirmed Shroud image fibres (Fanti et al. 2010, J. Imaging Sci. Technol.), it is chemically identical to the Shroud image mechanism.

PUBLICATION THRESHOLD: A confirmed C=C oxidation-dehydration signature on a page in the Codex Arundel burning mirror section, producing a suppressed-fluorescence spot of non-random geometry, would constitute peer-reviewable evidence that Leonardo conducted solar-scorching experiments on paper using his concave mirror technology. This is an independent and publishable discovery regardless of its connection to the Shroud.

